  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 10.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Give me now wisdom and knowledge",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The force of the opening of this verse, and the relation of it to the former, are both prejudiced by the \"now\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "עַתּה",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") being deposed from its right position as the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "first",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " word in the verse. For the rest of this verse, the parallel passage has \"an understanding heart\" in place of our \"wisdom ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "and knowledge",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ";\" and \"that I may discern between good and bad,\" in place of our ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "that I may go out and come in before this people",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In using the words, \"wisdom and knowledge,\" Solomon seems to have remembered well the prayer of his father (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 22:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). (For the pedigree of the simple and effective phrase, \"know how to go out and come in,\" see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 27:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 31:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 18:13, 16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 3:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It is at the same time refreshing to revisit the times when the most exalted nominal ruler was also the real ruler, as being the leader, the judge, the teacher in the highest sense, and \"the feeder\" of his people. Nor is it less refreshing to notice how, in Israel at least, the fact was so well recognized and honoured, that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "justice",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "to judge just judgment",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " lay at the deepest foundation of civil society. 2 Chronicles 1:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
